54
00:03:32,659 --> 00:03:37,392
London suffered the heaviest bombardment
since the 1940-'41 Blitz last night...

55
00:03:37,531 --> 00:03:39,931
...in German air raids over the capital.

56
00:03:40,600 --> 00:03:44,866
About 175 enemy planes made
scattered and indiscriminate attacks...

57
00:03:44,971 --> 00:03:49,271
...on London, the counties,
southeast England and East Anglia.

58
00:03:49,342 --> 00:03:51,276
The Last of the
BLONDE BOMBSHELLS

59
00:05:08,955 --> 00:05:12,322
- There you are, keep the change.
- Have a good day.

60
00:05:32,212 --> 00:05:34,942
So, have you made any plans, Mum?

61
00:05:35,815 --> 00:05:38,079
I think I'll go for the creme brulee.

62
00:05:38,251 --> 00:05:39,582
Oh, no.

63
00:05:39,919 --> 00:05:42,615
I didn't mean about the pudding.
I meant...

64
00:05:42,822 --> 00:05:44,084
Oh, life after death.

65
00:05:44,290 --> 00:05:45,757
Well, yes, I suppose so.

66
00:05:47,761 --> 00:05:51,492
Life goes on much as it did
when your father was alive.

67
00:05:52,165 --> 00:05:54,395
I still go to the library twice a week.

68
00:05:54,801 --> 00:05:57,167
I still watch the quiz programs
on television.

69
00:05:57,537 --> 00:05:59,334
Sometimes I get the answers right.

70
00:05:59,406 --> 00:06:02,739
I go out every Thursday with my children
to some trendy restaurant.

71
00:06:03,276 --> 00:06:04,800
And I weep when necessary.

72
00:06:05,612 --> 00:06:09,480
And I look after Joanna when
her parents want to expand their horizons.

73
00:06:09,749 --> 00:06:11,979
That's enough life
for a woman half my age.

74
00:06:12,852 --> 00:06:16,049
Can you have her on Friday?
We've got tickets to The Magic Flute.

75
00:06:16,122 --> 00:06:18,090
Fine, I'll cancel my darts night.

76
00:06:18,224 --> 00:06:19,589
You don't play darts.

77
00:06:26,533 --> 00:06:27,795
Isn't that lovely?

78
00:06:29,569 --> 00:06:30,558
What?

79
00:06:32,439 --> 00:06:36,205
If your pulse doesn't quicken when you
hear Hoagy Carmichael's Stardust...

80
00:06:36,276 --> 00:06:38,437
...then I've clearly failed as a mother.

81
00:06:40,880 --> 00:06:42,973
Thank you for lunch, my children.

82
00:06:43,483 --> 00:06:45,314
I'll see you next Thursday.

83
00:06:50,356 --> 00:06:52,586
Do you think she's turning into
a dotty old woman?

84
00:06:53,660 --> 00:06:54,888
She's always done it.

85
00:06:54,961 --> 00:06:58,453
You talk to her, she makes the right
noises but she's not listening.

86
00:06:58,565 --> 00:07:01,557
She's listening to what's inside her head.

87
00:07:02,469 --> 00:07:05,734
Whatever she's listening to now
is just a bit further away.

88
00:07:15,882 --> 00:07:18,350
You're much too young
to know those tunes.

89
00:07:19,052 --> 00:07:21,111
What makes you think I know them?

90
00:07:22,822 --> 00:07:25,518
You screwed up the changes
into the middle eight.

91
00:07:25,592 --> 00:07:27,025
It was a good try.

92
00:07:27,794 --> 00:07:29,489
You some sort of critic?

93
00:07:29,929 --> 00:07:31,123
No, don't worry.

94
00:07:32,899 --> 00:07:36,130
It's only if the audience notices,
you're in trouble.

95
00:07:51,951 --> 00:07:53,509
Don't give up.

96
00:09:12,999 --> 00:09:14,364
I didn't see you there.

97
00:09:14,634 --> 00:09:16,864
- That was amazing.
- Thank you.

98
00:09:18,705 --> 00:09:20,673
- May I touch?
- Well, of course.

99
00:09:22,242 --> 00:09:23,675
I didn't know.

100
00:09:25,778 --> 00:09:27,939
Remember that dance hall
I told you about?

101
00:09:28,014 --> 00:09:29,606
You Rascal, You.

102
00:09:30,250 --> 00:09:31,581
I played in the band.

103
00:09:32,218 --> 00:09:33,583
Did women do that then?

104
00:09:34,520 --> 00:09:37,785
What do you know about the war?
The 1939-'45?

105
00:09:37,857 --> 00:09:39,256
We beat Germany one-nil?

106
00:09:40,059 --> 00:09:42,084
It was an upside down world.

107
00:09:43,029 --> 00:09:46,624
Women drove ambulances
and worked in shipyards and...

108
00:09:47,667 --> 00:09:49,225
...I played in a band.

109
00:09:49,636 --> 00:09:51,797
We called ourselves
The Blonde Bombshells.

110
00:09:52,405 --> 00:09:53,531
Were you a star?

111
00:09:53,673 --> 00:09:55,140
We played on the wireless once.

112
00:09:55,208 --> 00:09:56,675
You were a star.

113
00:09:56,876 --> 00:09:59,208
Yes, damn it, I was a star.

114
00:10:27,473 --> 00:10:29,532
Grandma, why did you stop?

115
00:10:29,609 --> 00:10:31,600
I stopped when the war stopped.

116
00:10:32,512 --> 00:10:35,379
Then I was a wife and a mother
and a grandmother.

117
00:10:37,216 --> 00:10:39,844
It's just something I did before I grew up.

118
00:10:40,253 --> 00:10:41,720
But you carried on playing.

119
00:10:41,788 --> 00:10:45,451
Well, I used to practice
when your grandpa was out playing golf.

120
00:10:47,493 --> 00:10:50,053
But you're the first person to hear me for...

121
00:10:50,964 --> 00:10:52,261
...dear God...

122
00:10:52,332 --> 00:10:53,822
...nearly half a century.

123
00:10:54,767 --> 00:10:55,995
That's terrible.

124
00:10:58,638 --> 00:10:59,764
Joanna...

125
00:11:01,074 --> 00:11:02,666
...I need your advice.

126
00:11:02,875 --> 00:11:03,864
I'll try.

127
00:11:04,978 --> 00:11:07,742
What's the best way
of showing respect for the dead?

128
00:11:09,882 --> 00:11:12,077
That's easy. You go on living.

129
00:11:39,012 --> 00:11:40,377
You're truly amazing.

130
00:11:41,781 --> 00:11:45,512
- You're too good to be busking.
- I'm too old to have any other ambitions.

131
00:11:45,585 --> 00:11:47,075
Why don't you take half?

132
00:11:48,621 --> 00:11:52,955
Look, we play twice a week
and you buy the drinks, okay?

133
00:11:53,493 --> 00:11:54,517
Okay.

134
00:12:00,867 --> 00:12:02,459
I think this might be for you.

135
00:12:02,535 --> 00:12:03,467
Why?

136
00:12:03,569 --> 00:12:06,163
Because it says,
"Fancy a bit of fun, dearie?"

137
00:12:06,239 --> 00:12:08,104
Why should it be for me?

138
00:12:08,241 --> 00:12:12,405
If you say because I'm a woman,
I'll smash you on the head with the guitar.

139
00:12:12,545 --> 00:12:13,876
My glass is empty.

140
00:12:13,946 --> 00:12:17,746
- Same again?
- Please, let me have a look at that.

141
00:12:25,158 --> 00:12:26,216
Do you?

142
00:12:28,094 --> 00:12:29,118
Sorry?

143
00:12:30,430 --> 00:12:31,658
Fancy a bit of fun?

144
00:12:34,167 --> 00:12:35,794
Do you mind?

145
00:12:41,507 --> 00:12:43,441
It is Elizabeth, isn't it?

146
00:12:46,879 --> 00:12:48,642
Well, don't you remember?

147
00:12:49,282 --> 00:12:50,840
Metropole Ballroom?

148
00:12:51,484 --> 00:12:52,781
Moonlight Serenade?

149
00:12:53,286 --> 00:12:55,777
Boogie Woogie Bugle Boy
From Company B?

150
00:12:57,156 --> 00:12:58,145
Patrick.

151
00:12:58,658 --> 00:13:00,148
You see? You do remember.

152
00:13:00,526 --> 00:13:02,426
The man we were all warned about.

153
00:13:03,196 --> 00:13:05,323
At least offer me the hand of friendship.

154
00:13:05,498 --> 00:13:06,965
I might never see it again.

155
00:13:14,340 --> 00:13:16,501
If you're going to play, play it properly.

156
00:13:17,110 --> 00:13:20,045
I was just trying to catch
the spirit of the moment.

157
00:13:20,113 --> 00:13:21,637
Are you gonna introduce me?

158
00:13:22,448 --> 00:13:23,437
Paul...

159
00:13:24,016 --> 00:13:26,143
...down-and-out street musician...

160
00:13:26,252 --> 00:13:29,619
...Patrick, venerable friend and war hero.

161
00:13:30,089 --> 00:13:32,614
That's cool.
What did you do in the war, Patrick?

162
00:13:34,560 --> 00:13:36,187
I was a Blonde Bombshell.

163
00:13:36,262 --> 00:13:38,822
"When you're dead in your grave

164
00:13:38,931 --> 00:13:41,126
"No more women will you crave

165
00:13:41,234 --> 00:13:43,668
"I'll be glad when you're gone

166
00:13:44,337 --> 00:13:46,134
"Glad when you're gone

167
00:13:46,839 --> 00:13:50,172
"Glad when you're gone
You rascal, you"

168
00:13:56,149 --> 00:13:57,810
Here, let me take that.

169
00:13:59,152 --> 00:14:01,848
Would you believe I recognized
the way you play?

170
00:14:02,388 --> 00:14:03,548
That sound?

171
00:14:03,856 --> 00:14:05,255
Sensual, erotic.

172
00:14:05,324 --> 00:14:07,690
Don't be silly.
What are you doing around here?

173
00:14:07,760 --> 00:14:08,988
The betting shop.

174
00:14:09,061 --> 00:14:10,790
I'll give you a lift.

175
00:14:13,533 --> 00:14:14,864
In that?

176
00:14:15,234 --> 00:14:17,031
We'll drop off at my place.

177
00:14:17,937 --> 00:14:18,961
Come on.

178
00:14:25,611 --> 00:14:29,206
Don't worry about all that.
It's my concessionary parking system.

179
00:14:31,050 --> 00:14:32,347
- You in?
- Yeah.

180
00:15:10,456 --> 00:15:13,789
So, how come a nice girl like you
is reduced to working the streets?

181
00:15:15,461 --> 00:15:18,259
It's because I said
"fuck" at George's funeral.

182
00:15:21,167 --> 00:15:24,227
I assume George is your late,
lamented husband?

183
00:15:24,303 --> 00:15:25,327
Yes.

184
00:15:26,272 --> 00:15:27,762
He treat you well?

185
00:15:28,774 --> 00:15:32,540
Well, he was kind and decent
and generous and law-abiding.

186
00:15:32,645 --> 00:15:33,634
Boring?

187
00:15:33,713 --> 00:15:35,977
- Mind your own business.
- Thought so.

188
00:15:45,391 --> 00:15:46,949
This is where you live?

189
00:15:47,026 --> 00:15:48,323
Yes, it's...

190
00:15:48,394 --> 00:15:52,057
They call it "Grace and Favor Residence".
My father had the grace to die and...

191
00:15:52,131 --> 00:15:54,361
...did me the favor of leaving it to me.

192
00:15:55,334 --> 00:15:56,494
Thank you.

193
00:15:57,837 --> 00:16:01,034
I would be deeply honored
if you would step across the threshold...

194
00:16:01,107 --> 00:16:03,098
...and let my woodworm see you.

195
00:16:05,344 --> 00:16:07,244
- Hi, Patrick.
- Hello, darling.

196
00:16:08,581 --> 00:16:10,446
Didn't know you had a secret.

197
00:16:12,818 --> 00:16:14,149
How's the masterpiece?

198
00:16:14,220 --> 00:16:15,448
Bloody arm came off.

199
00:16:18,658 --> 00:16:20,558
Who exactly is "darling"?

200
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:23,151
Carol. Lodger. Art student.

201
00:16:23,229 --> 00:16:28,098
Tomorrow, 4:00, Hereford, Billie's Bounce.

202
00:16:28,401 --> 00:16:29,766
- Shirt.
- Noted.

203
00:16:30,136 --> 00:16:31,228
Ma'am.

204
00:16:32,438 --> 00:16:33,700
A true artist.

205
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:36,538
Ex-jockey. Tipster in residence.

206
00:16:37,310 --> 00:16:41,679
Known as "the wee man" and banned
from every race course in the country.

207
00:16:43,949 --> 00:16:44,916
But...

208
00:16:45,618 --> 00:16:48,712
...the real glory is found downstairs
in my personal crypt.

209
00:16:48,788 --> 00:16:51,416
There's something
very special I want to show you.

210
00:16:51,490 --> 00:16:52,684
What a surprise.

211
00:16:52,758 --> 00:16:55,750
Don't be silly.
I never go all the way on the first date.

212
00:17:13,312 --> 00:17:15,212
- The same kit?
- Yes.

213
00:17:15,581 --> 00:17:17,640
Of course, I remember the roses.

214
00:17:18,551 --> 00:17:21,179
- Do you still play?
- Only when nobody listens.

215
00:17:34,800 --> 00:17:36,427
You were really pretty.

216
00:17:37,937 --> 00:17:39,131
So were you.

217
00:17:39,672 --> 00:17:41,333
Why did you do this?

218
00:17:41,674 --> 00:17:45,337
Working with The Blonde Bombshells
was the happiest time of my life.

219
00:17:45,411 --> 00:17:47,038
Life's been that bad?

220
00:17:47,279 --> 00:17:51,079
I've been to prison once.
Married twice. Bankrupt three times.

221
00:17:51,150 --> 00:17:53,118
- Ain't you got fun?
- Yeah, lots of fun.

222
00:17:55,221 --> 00:17:56,984
But those were the days.

223
00:17:57,189 --> 00:17:58,588
Best days.

224
00:17:59,992 --> 00:18:02,790
I'll bet you a dollar
to a donut you think so, too.

225
00:18:02,862 --> 00:18:06,059
If I admit that, it's like admitting
I've wasted most of my life.

226
00:18:06,132 --> 00:18:08,032
Well, go ahead, admit it.

227
00:18:08,567 --> 00:18:11,331
I've wasted mine
and enjoyed every minute of it.

228
00:18:13,639 --> 00:18:15,368
Well, I can't tell a lie.

229
00:18:16,375 --> 00:18:20,436
I was showing off to my granddaughter
about being on the wireless.

230
00:18:20,913 --> 00:18:23,973
That was your fault
for being beautiful and talented.

231
00:18:24,049 --> 00:18:25,846
Yes, I remember.

232
00:18:56,215 --> 00:18:57,239
Excuse me.

233
00:18:57,316 --> 00:18:59,307
- You do play awfully well.
- Thank you.

234
00:18:59,385 --> 00:19:01,012
Is this bastard bothering you?

235
00:19:01,086 --> 00:19:02,553
I'm from BBC.

236
00:19:03,055 --> 00:19:05,990
Beg your pardon. I took you for a civilian.

237
00:19:06,058 --> 00:19:07,855
Back to your place, sweetheart.

238
00:19:07,927 --> 00:19:11,522
I wonder whether you and your orchestra
would be interested in broadcasting.

239
00:19:11,597 --> 00:19:14,088
I have to say that girl plays beautifully.

240
00:19:14,233 --> 00:19:16,861
- She's better than many a chap.
- And a lot prettier.

241
00:19:16,936 --> 00:19:19,871
And it would be a joy and a delight
to do business with you.

242
00:19:19,939 --> 00:19:22,965
Give me 30 seconds to wind them up
and set them going.

243
00:19:24,276 --> 00:19:27,302
The next dance will be a quickstep.
Take it away, girls.

244
00:19:27,847 --> 00:19:30,315
A one, a two, a one, two, three, four.

245
00:19:33,419 --> 00:19:37,185
Come to the dressing room.
We'll compare our arrangements.

246
00:19:42,561 --> 00:19:45,587
"Take it away, girls."
Nobody ever says that now.

247
00:19:45,698 --> 00:19:47,598
Long time since we were girls.

248
00:19:47,666 --> 00:19:50,191
I suppose technically speaking,
I never was.

249
00:19:52,004 --> 00:19:55,838
You know, I've been thinking about it
more and more since the funeral.

250
00:19:56,675 --> 00:19:58,870
We were heroic for a while.

251
00:20:00,246 --> 00:20:01,645
Nobody told us.

252
00:20:04,016 --> 00:20:06,678
When shall we two meet again,
Sunday lunch?

253
